# Huellitas API — Cursor Rules

## Stack
Node.js v22 LTS, Express v4, TypeScript strict mode, PostgreSQL 16 + PostGIS, Better Auth, Zod v3, Winston, Sentry.

## Architecture (Layered — strictly enforced)
Routes → Controllers → Services → Repositories → Database

Rules:
- Routes: define HTTP verbs, paths, attach middleware
- Controllers: extract request data, call services, format response. NO business logic.
- Services: orchestrate business logic. NO SQL. NO direct req/res handling.
- Repositories: execute SQL queries only. Return typed domain objects.
- Database: pool configuration only.

## Naming Conventions
- Files: kebab-case (users.service.ts, pets.repository.ts)
- Classes/Interfaces: PascalCase
- Functions/methods: camelCase
- Constants: SCREAMING_SNAKE_CASE
- Database columns: snake_case
- Route params: camelCase in TypeScript, snake_case in SQL

## TypeScript
- Enable strict mode
- All function parameters and return types must be explicit
- Use `unknown` for errors, narrow with type guards
- Define Zod schemas for ALL external input (body, query, params)
- Infer TypeScript types from Zod schemas: `type CreatePetDto = z.infer<typeof createPetSchema>`

## Input Validation (MANDATORY)
- Validate ALL inputs at the route level using Zod
- Use `validate(schema)` middleware factory
- Never access req.body without validation
- Validate query params (lat, lng, radius) with number ranges

## Error Handling (Centralized)
- Throw typed errors from services/repositories: `throw new NotFoundError('Pet not found')`
- Centralized error middleware in src/middleware/error.middleware.ts handles all errors
- Never return raw database errors to client
- Log errors with Winston including request ID, user ID, stack trace
- Send to Sentry for unexpected errors

## Repository Pattern (Strict)
- ALL SQL lives in repositories only
- Controllers and services must NEVER contain SQL or raw pg queries
- Repository methods return typed domain objects (not raw pg rows)
- Use parameterized queries always (never string interpolation in SQL)
- Use PostGIS functions for geo queries (ST_DWithin, ST_MakePoint)

## Immutability
- Never mutate function arguments
- Return new objects from transformations
- Repositories return new objects from DB rows

## Security (CRITICAL)
- Helmet on all routes
- Rate limiting: auth (5/min), API (100/min/user), upload (10/min)
- CORS: whitelist only known origins
- No sensitive data in logs (no passwords, no full tokens)
- Environment variables validated at startup via Zod (fail fast)
- Parameterized queries everywhere (SQL injection prevention)

## Logging
- Use Winston logger (src/config/logger.ts) — never use console.log
- Always include: requestId, userId (if authenticated), action description
- Log levels: debug (dev only), info (operations), warn (degraded), error (failures)
- Never log: passwords, tokens, private keys, full request bodies with sensitive fields

## Testing
- Write tests BEFORE implementation (TDD)
- Integration tests: full HTTP requests via Supertest (routes → DB)
- Unit tests: services with mocked repositories
- Repository tests: hit test database (real PostgreSQL)
- Coverage: 80% minimum
- Test naming: `describe('PetsService', () => { describe('#createPet', () => { it('creates a pet for the owner', ...) }) })`

## Common Anti-Patterns to AVOID
- SQL in controllers or services
- Business logic in controllers
- Direct console.log (use Winston)
- Hardcoded secrets or config values (use env.ts)
- Ignoring async errors (always await and handle)
- Fat repositories (one method per query, max 50 lines)
